<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>Jim Nielsen: designer, developer, problem solver.</title>
  <meta name="description" content="Personal website of Jim Nielsen" />
  <meta name="author" content="Jim Nielsen" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/assets/css/reset.css" />
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/assets/css/styles.css" />
  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Open+Sans:400,600|PT+Serif:400,400i" rel="stylesheet" />
</head>
<body>
  <main class="wrapper main">
    <header class="header">
      <div class="header__graphic">
        <img src="/assets/img/logo.png" width="255" height="126" />
        <img src="/assets/img/profile.jpg" width="490" height="540" />
        <canvas id="canvas"></canvas>
      </div>
      
      <h1>Jim Nielsen: designer, developer, problem solver.</h1>
      <h2>Currently: Director of Design &amp; UI Architecture @ Insight Catastrophe Group.</h2>
    
      <nav class="nav">
        <ul>
          <% sections.forEach(({ id, title }) => { %>
            <li>
              <a href="#<%- id %>"><%- title %></a>
            </li>
          <% }) %>
        </ul>
      </nav>
      
      <p><em>Who are you?</em> The answer you’re probably looking for is “I am a web designer who also codes.” But what I really do is solve problems and add value to projects I work on. And that’s probably one of the less intersting facts about me, but you know, this is a website where I talk about myself professionally, so I have to say these things.</p>
      <p><em>What are your skills?</em> My practical skills aren’t what’s interesting about me. Yes, I design visual interfaces and leverage principles of design, color theory, and typography. I write code and intimately understand HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. But my skills are tools to and end: to solve problems and provide value.</p>
      <p><em>What’s your expertise?</em> My expertise lies in synthensizing knowledge across perceivedly disparate boundaries. “Visual designer”, “Front-end Developer”, and “Product Manager”, I assume all those responsibilities in order to add value to a business, to enhance a company’s culture, to bring clarity to a project, or to just get along with humans (something often perceived as a difficult task for people who write instructions for machines).</p>
      <p><em>How are you, you know, as a human?</em> Don’t take it from me, here are the words of a peer when I was departing a previous employer:</p>
      <blockquote><p>Gonna be a real bummer here w/o you. You bring a lot of great design, and a lot of not-being-an-asshole-ness.</p></blockquote>
      <p><em>Do you have anything else to say?</em> Yes, in fact, glad you asked. Everything I am as a designer, developer, tech person, and just general human is a result of the wonderful people who I've crossed paths with in my life. I've worked with some of the most <a href="">thoughtful</a>, <a href="">funny</a>, <a href="">esoteric</a>, <a href="">kind</a>, and <a href="">witty</a> people you’ll ever meet. More than any project I've worked on, I'm proud of the people I've worked with and learned from. I'm sure you, dear reader, would be a wonderful person I could learn from as well.</p>
      <p>— Jim Nielsen, August 2, 2018</p>
    </header>

    <% sections.forEach(({ id, url, title, data }) => { %>
        <section class="section clearfix" id="<%- id %>">
          <h2 class="section__header">
            
            
            
              <%- title %>
            
          </h2>
          <ul class="section__content">
              
            <!-- Dribbble -->
            <% if (id === "dribbble") { %>
              <% data.forEach(({ description, created_at, html_url, images: { normal }, title }) => { %>
                <li class="item">
                  <a class="item__img" href="<%- html_url %>">
                    <img
                      src="<%- normal %>"
                      alt="<%- title %>"
                      title="<%- title %> on Dribbble"
                      width="400"
                      height="300"
                    />
                  </a>
                  <div class="item__content">
                    <h3 class="title">
                      <a href="<%- html_url %>" class="link">
                        <%- title %>
                      </a>
                    </h3>
                    <p class="byline"><%- created_at %></p>
                    <div class="description"><%- description %></div>
                  </div>
                </li>
              <% }) %>
              
              <li class="view-more">
                <a href="<%- url %>" class="link">
                  View more at <%- url %> ›
                </a>
              </li>
            <% } %>

            <!-- Employment -->
            <% if (id === "employment") { %>
              <% data.forEach(({ byline, company, companyUrl, description, projects, title }) => { %>
              <li class="item">
                <div class="item__img">
                  <img src="/assets/img/employment/<%- company.toLowerCase().replace(/ /g, "-") %>.png" />
                </div>
                <div class="item__content">
                  <h3 class="title">
                    <%- title %> @ <a href="<%- companyUrl %>" class="link"><%- company %></a>
                  </h3>
                  <p class="byline"><%- byline %></p>
                  <p class="description"><%- description %></p>
            
                  <% if (projects) { %>
                  <ul class="projects clearfix">
                    <% projects.forEach(project => { %>
                    <li>
                        <h4>
                          Project: <%- project.title %>
                        </h4>
            
                        <p class="description">
                          <%- project.description %>
                          Tools: <%- project.tools %>.
                        </p>
            
                        <% if (project.links) { %>
                          <ul class="links">
                            <% project.links.forEach(link => { %>
                            <li>
                              <a href="<%- link.url %>" class="link">
                                <%- link.title %>
                              </a>
                            </li>
                            <% }) %>
                          </ul>
                        <% } %>
                    </li>
                    <% }) %>
                  </ul>
                  <% } %>
                </div>
              </li>
              <% }) %>
            <% } %>
          </ul>
        </section>
    <% }) %>
  
  </main>
      
  <aside class='wrapper'>
    <div class='skills'>
      <strong>
        > ls -skills
      </strong>
      <ul>
        <% skills.forEach(({ name, capability, divider }) => { %>
          <li class="<%- divider ? 'divider' : '' %>">
            <span>-<%- capability %></span>
            <span>jim-nielsen</span>
            <span><%- name %></span>
          </li>
        <% }) %>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </aside>
  

  <footer class='wrapper footer'>
    <p>
      Want to contact me? Email <a href='mailto:jimniels@gmail.com'>jimniels at gmail</a> or tweet <a href='http://twitter.com/jimniels'>@jimniels</a>
    </p>
  </footer>

  <script defer type="text/javascript" src="/assets/js/draw.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
    
    
    
    
    